年在他的家乡享年84岁。"},"hr":{"1400–1484":"1400.–1484.","1410–1497":"1410–1497","–1506":"–1506","1420–1470":"1420.–1470.","1425–1491":"1425.–1491","1384–1420":"1384–1420.","1388–1466":"1388–1466.","1484":"1484.","1384":"1384","1470":"1470.","1491":"1491","1425":"1425.","1400":"1400.","1466":"1466.","1455":"1455","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","1420":"1420.","1497":"1497","about 1453":"oko 1453.","1506":"1506","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Sissinghurst, Kent, England":"Milkhouse Street, Kent, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"cs":{"1400–1484":"1400–1484","1410–1497":"1410–1497","–1506":"–1506","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1425–1491":"1425–1491","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1388–1466":"1388–1466","1484":"1484","1384":"1384","1470":"1470","1491":"1491","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","about 1453":"okolo 1453","1506":"1506","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, Anglie","Sissinghurst, Kent, England":"Milkhouse Street, Kent, Anglie","England":"Anglie","Kent, England":"Kent, Anglie"},"da":{"1400–1484":"1400–1484","1410–1497":"1410–1497","–1506":"–1506","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1425–1491":"1425–1491","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1388–1466":"1388–1466","1484":"1484","1384":"1384","1470":"1470","1491":"1491","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","about 1453":"omkring 1453","1506":"1506","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Sissinghurst, Kent, England":"Milkhouse Street, Kent, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"nl":{"1400–1484":"1400–1484","1410–1497":"1410–1497","–1506":"–1506","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1425–1491":"1425–1491","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1388–1466":"1388–1466","1484":"1484","1384":"1384","1470":"1470","1491":"1491","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","about 1453":"circa 1453","1506":"1506","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Sissinghurst, Kent, England":"Milkhouse Street, Kent, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"en":{"1400–1484":"1400–1484","1410–1497":"1410–1497","–1506":"–1506","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1425–1491":"1425–1491","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1388–1466":"1388–1466","1484":"1484","1384":"1384","1470":"1470","1491":"1491","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","about 1453":"about 1453","1506":"1506","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Sissinghurst, Kent, England":"Milkhouse Street, Kent, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name, from Middle English <i>bakere</i>, Old English <i>bæcere</i>, a derivative of <i>bacan</i> ‘to bake’. It may have been used for someone whose special task in the kitchen of a great house or castle was the baking of bread, but since most humbler households did their own baking in the Middle Ages, it may also have referred to the owner of a communal oven used by the whole village. The right to be in charge of this and exact money or loaves in return for its use was in many parts of the country a hereditary feudal privilege. Compare   Miller  . Less often the surname may have been acquired by someone noted for baking particularly fine bread or by a baker of pottery or bricks.","Americanized form (translation into English) of surnames meaning ‘baker’, for example Dutch   Bakker  , German   Becker   and   Beck  , French   Boulanger   and <b>Bélanger</b> (see   Belanger  ), Czech <b>Pekař</b>, Slovak <b>Pekár</b>, and Croatian   Pekar  .","History: Baker was established as an early immigrant surname in Puritan New England. Among others, two men called Remember Baker (father and son) lived at Woodbury, CT, in the early 17th century, and an Alexander Baker arrived in Boston, MA, in 1635."],"variants":[{"name":"Miller","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a miller. The standard modern vocabulary word represents the northern Middle English term <i>miller</i>, an agent derivative of <i>mille</i> ‘mill’, reinforced by Old Norse <i>mylnari</i> (see   Milner  ). In southern, western, and central England   Millward   (literally, ‘mill keeper’) was the usual term. In North America, the surname <i>Miller</i> has absorbed many cognate surnames from other languages, for example German <b>Müller</b> (see   Mueller  ), Dutch   Mulder   and   Molenaar  , French   Meunier  , Italian   Molinaro  , Spanish   Molinero  , Hungarian <b>Molnár</b> (see   Molnar  ), Slovenian, Croatian, and Serbian   Mlinar  , Polish <b>Młynarz</b> or <b>Młynarczyk</b> (see   Mlynarczyk  ). <i>Miller</i> (including in the senses below) is the seventh most frequent surname in the US.","South German, Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of <b>Müller</b> ‘miller’ (see   Mueller  ) and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in other European countries, notably in Poland, Denmark, France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), and Czechia; compare 3 below.","Americanized form of Polish, Czech, Croatian, Serbian, and Slovenian   Miler   ‘miller’, a surname of German origin."]},{"name":"Baxter","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>baxter</i> ‘baker’ (from Old English <i>bæcestre</i> ‘baker’, earlier ‘female baker’, the feminine equivalent of <i>bæcere</i>). Compare   Baker  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Simon Baker 1st was born in 1400, in Faversham, Kent, England, his father, Thomas Baker III, was 16 and his mother, Margaret Thomas, was 12. He married Alice d'Arderne about 1453, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1484, in his hometown, at the age of 84."},"et":{"1400–1484":"1400–1484","1410–1497":"1410–1497","–1506":"–1506","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1425–1491":"1425–1491","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1388–1466":"1388–1466","1484":"1484","1384":"1384","1470":"1470","1491":"1491","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","about 1453":"umbes 1453","1506":"1506","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Sissinghurst, Kent, England":"Milkhouse Street, Kent, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"1400–1484":"1400–1484","1410–1497":"1410–1497","–1506":"–1506","1420–1470":"1420–